03843nam a22005295i 9780773575486DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20062006xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735754867 a10.1515/97807735754862doi  a(DE-B1597)654970  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1032.D966 2007eb 7aPOL0320002bisacsh04a971.0391 aCraig, Gerald M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLord Durham's Report :bText Abridged by Gerald M. Craig /cGerald M. Craig, Guy Laforest, Janet Ajzenstat. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2006] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (261 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCarleton Library Series ;v20800tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIntroduction to the 2006 Edition -- tIntroduction to the 1963 Edition -- tCommission -- tReport -- tAfterword Lord Durham, French Canada, and Quebec: Remembering the Past, Debating the Future -- tSuggestions for Further Reading -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn his famous 1839 call to reform, John George Lambton, Earl of Durham, recommended that Upper and Lower Canada be accorded responsible government by uniting the two provinces under a single legislative assembly - a union which would also bring about the assimilation of the French-Canadians. The Report has been criticized ever since - from British imperialists who found it dangerously liberal to French Canadians who despised Durham for his presumed racism. This new edition of Gerald Craig's abridgement retains his 1963 introduction and adds essays that debate Durham's political assumptions and goals, re-examine the philosophical and historical context in which the Report was created, and review the Report's reception and influence. Janet Ajzenstat reconsiders the report in the context of nineteenth-century debates about the relation between culture and political institutions, arguing that Durham should be seen as a progressive universalist opposed to the divisions of race and creed who wanted to give more freedom to French- and English-Canadians alike. Guy Laforest re-examines the report in terms of British liberal imperialism and twentieth-century English-Canadian perspectives to argue that Durham was a one-sided sociologist and the first in long line who used liberalism for imperialist purposes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Essays.2bisacsh1 aAjzenstat, Janet, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aAjzenstat, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraig, Gerald M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraig, Gerald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaforest, Guy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357548640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773575486423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773575486/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles